article.headline: Bluejays win despite lackluster effort, coach says

images.caption: Creighton's Kellen Milner, right, beats Delaware State's Miles Davis to the ball.

article.linkText: Creighton lets its No. 24-ranking do the talking
article.story: OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Creighton's top player wasn't much of a factor, and the Bluejays (No. 24 ESPN/USA Today; No. 20 Associated Press) committed 19 turnovers. They still won easily Monday night, but that wasn't much consolation to coach Dana Altman after the 68-48 victory over Delaware State. Creighton is 8-0 for the ninth time in school history. ''The first seven ballgames we came out with a lot of purpose and intensity,'' Altman said. ''Tonight, it wasn't there. It shows we have a lot of work to do. We were exposed a little bit. When we go full blast, we can play with most people. When we let down, we're not big enough or good enough to be successful.'' Brody Deren scored 14 points to lead the Bluejays, while Kellen Miliner added 11 and DeAnthony Bowden had 10. Creighton's Kyle Korver, averaging a team-leading 18.4 points, finished with seven after being held scoreless for the first 18 minutes. Miles Davis and Carlos Hawkins each had 11 points for the Hornets (2-5). The Bluejays made 10 of their first 12 shots to open the second half and pulled away after coming out flat at the start of the game. ''We hit a couple shots in the second half,'' Altman said, ''and that seemed to get our heads up.'' Creighton missed eight of its first nine shots while falling behind 8-2. ''At first, we were in unfamiliar territory,'' Deren said. ''You miss a few shots and get your flow disrupted, and it takes a while to get it back.'' Delaware State committed 15 of its 22 turnovers in the first half as the Bluejays recovered to take a 31-25 lead. ''They turned up the intensity level,'' Delaware State coach Greg Jackson said. ''Obviously, we got beat by a much better ballteam.'' The Hornets turned the ball over four times on eight possessions as the Bluejays tied it 10-10. Mike Grimes scored five consecutive points and Larry House converted on a three-point play to pull the Bluejays even. Bowden's three-point play gave Creighton its first lead, 15-14, with 6:29 left in the half. Joe Dabbert's putback dunk made it 25-17, and 3-pointers by Korver and Miliner made it 31-19. Delaware State, which shot 55 percent in the first half, scored the last six points of the half to make it a six-point game. Creighton, 2-for-13 from 3-point range in the first half, made three in a row to open the second half and take a 40-28 lead. The Bluejays finished off the Hornets with a 12-0 run that saw Miliner hit two 3s and score eight points. Korver, who finished 3-for-8 from the field, was held to his lowest point total of the season. Delaware State used a combination of defenses, including a box-and-one, to hold him in check. ''When they take Kyle away,'' Miliner said, ''everybody else has to do his part.'' Creighton's bench contributed 34 points. ''We brought a lot of energy,'' Miliner said. We just flew around, especially on defense.''
